example.p:
For the scalar \alpha=7 and the matrix A,
                A&=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                2&8\\
                -3&5\\0&1
                \end{bmatrix}
                &
                \alpha A&=
                7\begin{bmatrix}2&8\\-3&5\\0&1\end{bmatrix}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix}7(2)&7(8)\\7(-3)&7(5)\\7(0)&7(1)\end{bmatrix}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix}14&56\\-21&35\\0&7\end{bmatrix}
            .

For the 2\times 3 matrix A, we compute the conjugate of A, \conjugate{A}.
                A&=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                2-i & 3 & 5+4i\\
                -3+6i & 2-3i & 0
                \end{bmatrix}
                &
                \conjugate{A}&=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                2+i & 3 & 5-4i\\
                -3-6i & 2+3i & 0
                \end{bmatrix}

statement.p:
Perform the following matrix computation.(6)
                \begin{bmatrix}
                2 & -2 & 8 & 1 \\
                4 & 5 & -1 & 3\\
                7 & -3 & 0 & 2
                \end{bmatrix}
                +
                (-2)
                \begin{bmatrix}
                2 & 7 & 1 & 2\\
                3 & -1 & 0 & 5\\
                1 & 7 & 3 & 3
                \end{bmatrix}

Compute the transpose of the matrix below.\begin{bmatrix}
                6 & 8 & 4 \\
                -2 & 1 & 0 \\
                9 & -5 & 6
                \end{bmatrix}

Solve the given vector equation for x, or explain why no solution exists.2 \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 & 3 \\ 0 & 4 & 2 \end{bmatrix} -
                3 \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 & 2 \\ 0 & 1 & x \end{bmatrix}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix} -1 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 5 & -2 \end{bmatrix}

solution.p:
The given equation
                    \begin{bmatrix} -1 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 5  & -2 \end{bmatrix}
                    &=
                    2\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 & 3 \\ 0 & 4 & 2 \end{bmatrix} -
                    3\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 & 2 \\ 0 & 1 & x \end{bmatrix}
                    =
                    \begin{bmatrix} -1 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 &5  & 4 - 3x \end{bmatrix}
                is valid only if 4 - 3x = -2.  Thus, the only solution is x = 2.

statement.p:
Solve the given matrix equation for \alpha, or explain why no solution exists.\alpha\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 3 & 4 \\ 2 & 1 & -1 \end{bmatrix} +
                \begin{bmatrix} 4 & 3 & -6 \\ 0 & 1 & 1 \end{bmatrix}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix} 7 & 12 & 6 \\ 6 & 4 & -2 \end{bmatrix}

solution.p:
The given equation
                    \begin{bmatrix} 7 & 12 & 6\\ 6 & 4 & -2 \end{bmatrix}
                    &=
                    \alpha\begin{bmatrix}
                    1 & 3 & 4 \\
                     2 & 1 & -1
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    +
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    4 & 3 & -6 \\
                    0 & 1 & 1
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    &=
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    \alpha & 3\alpha & 4\alpha \\
                    2\alpha & \alpha & -\alpha
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    +
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    4 & 3 & -6 \\
                    0 & 1 & 1
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    &=
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    4 + \alpha & 3 + 3\alpha & -6 + 4\alpha \\
                    2\alpha & 1 + \alpha & 1 - \alpha
                    \end{bmatrix}
                leads to the 6 equations in \alpha
                    4 + \alpha &= 7
                    3 + 3\alpha &= 12
                    -6 + 4\alpha &= 6
                    2\alpha &= 6
                    1 + \alpha &= 4
                    1 - \alpha &= -2
                .  The only value that solves all 6 equations is \alpha = 3, which is the solution to the original matrix equation.

statement.p:
Solve the given matrix equation for \alpha, or explain why no solution exists.\alpha \begin{bmatrix} 3 & 1 \\ 2 & 0 \\ 1 & 4\end{bmatrix} -
                \begin{bmatrix} 4 & 1 \\ 3 & 2 \\ 0 & 1 \end{bmatrix}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix} 2 & 1 \\ 1 & -2 \\ 2 & 6 \end{bmatrix}

Find \alpha and \beta that solve the following equation.\alpha\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 4 & 1 \end{bmatrix} +
                \beta\begin{bmatrix} 2 & 1 \\ 3 & 1 \end{bmatrix}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix} -1 & 4 \\ 6 & 1 \end{bmatrix}

Show that the set S is linearly independent in M_{22}.S=\set{
                    \begin{bmatrix}1&0\\0&0\end{bmatrix},\,
                    \begin{bmatrix}0&1\\0&0\end{bmatrix},\,
                    \begin{bmatrix}0&0\\1&0\end{bmatrix},\,
                    \begin{bmatrix}0&0\\0&1\end{bmatrix}
                    }.

Determine if the set S below is linearly independent in M_{23}.\set{
                    \begin{bmatrix} -2 & 3 & 4 \\ -1 & 3 & -2 \end{bmatrix},\,
                    \begin{bmatrix} 4 & -2 & 2 \\ 0 & -1 & 1 \end{bmatrix},\,
                    \begin{bmatrix}-1 & -2 & -2 \\ 2 & 2 & 2 \end{bmatrix},\,
                    \begin{bmatrix}-1 & 1 & 0 \\ -1 & 0 & -2 \end{bmatrix},\,
                    \begin{bmatrix}-1 & 2 & -2 \\ 0 & -1 & -2 \end{bmatrix}
                    }

Determine if the matrix A is in the span of S.  In other words, is  A\in\spn{S}?  If so write A as a linear combination of the elements of S.
                        A&=
                        \begin{bmatrix}
                        -13 & 24 & 2\\
                        -8 & -2 & -20
                        \end{bmatrix}
                        S&=\set{
                        \begin{bmatrix} -2 & 3 & 4 \\ -1 & 3 & -2 \end{bmatrix},\,
                        \begin{bmatrix} 4 & -2 & 2 \\ 0 & -1 & 1 \end{bmatrix},\,
                        \begin{bmatrix}-1 & -2 & -2 \\ 2 & 2 & 2 \end{bmatrix},\,
                        \begin{bmatrix}-1 & 1 & 0 \\ -1 & 0 & -2 \end{bmatrix},\,
                        \begin{bmatrix}-1 & 2 & -2 \\ 0 & -1 & -2 \end{bmatrix}
                        }

solution.p:
The matrix A is in the span of S, since
                        \begin{bmatrix} -13 & 24 & 2 \\ -8 & -2 & -20 \end{bmatrix}
                        &=
                        2\begin{bmatrix} -2 & 3 & 4 \\ -1 & 3 & -2 \end{bmatrix}
                        -2\begin{bmatrix} 4 & -2 & 2 \\ 0 & -1 & 1 \end{bmatrix}
                        -3\begin{bmatrix} -1 & -2 & -2 \\ 2 & 2 & 2 \end{bmatrix}
                        + 4\begin{bmatrix} -1 & 2 & -2 \\0 & -1 & -2 \end{bmatrix}
                    Note that if we were to write a complete linear combination of all of the matrices in S, then the fourth matrix would have a zero coefficient.

statement.p:
Define a subset of M_{33} byU_{33}=\setparts{
                    A\in M_{33}
                    }{
                    \matrixentry{A}{ij}=0\text{ whenever }i\gt j
                    }.  Find a set R so that R is linearly independent and \spn{R}=U_{33}.
